erver of the political and social ways of the North. The journal reveals his awareness, unusual in his time, of the adverse effects on Native peoples and their environment of the coming of the Europeans. Hood's paintings capture the beauty as well as the harshness of the North. His bird paintings in particular are of special artistic and historical interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNatural historyxNorthwest, Canadian. 0aNatural historyzNorthwest, Canadian. 0aSciences naturellesxNord-Ouest canadien. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aFranklin, Lieut., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHood, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aR.N.,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356491640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564916/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles